HEADWORD: Gangrene
<hw>Gan"grene</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>gangr⟦egrave⟧ne</ets>, L. <ets>gangraena</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/, fr.
<?/ to gnaw, eat; cf. Skr. <ets>gras</ets>, <ets>gar</ets>, to devour,
and E. <ets>voracious</ets>, also <ets>canker</ets>, <pos>n.</pos>, in
sense 3.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A term formerly restricted to
mortification of the soft tissues which has not advanced so far as to
produce complete loss of vitality; but now applied to mortification of
the soft parts in any stage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gangrene</ent>⟦br⟧

